Yep, all the presented numbers are scan-level. Slice level can't be quantified on the qure25k and cq500 datasets because radiologists reads on the both are only scan level.
Ah, whoops, I meant scan-level FDR". We can't know slice level with given info."

3) downsampling spatial and greyscale dimensions, but mitigating the latter by presenting the model with human-optimised window settings (for seeing brain, bone, and blood). This is the kind of fix I like, simple, informed, probably works very well.

Interesting choices: 1) using RF to combine slice predictions to predict per scan. Much of the combining classifiers"/"fusion" literature suggests simple average is as good or better. 2) ResNet-18 is pretty old, would expect bigger deeper nets to do better. ?computational limit"

Would have liked to see a prevalence-variant metric (like precision), but enough info is given to calculate it. Prec for ICH on Qure25k @high sens is 77%, and high spec is 90%. So slice-level FDR (% of cases incorrectly called positive) is 23% / 10% at clinical prevalence.

Nice paper! Demographics, good explanation of data and findings, not oversold (loving Figure 3 - attached). One weakness not mentioned - no normal" class results. We can assume there are lots of negative slices, but the actual numbers would be nice (I'm too lazy to calculate). pic.twitter.com/1GaHGmsTRL"
